        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="608" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d608">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>The mass escape of North Korean nonrepatriate <gloss target="#t_POWs1"
                        >POWs</gloss> occasioned a number of high-level communications which were
                    either made public at the time or which have been released subsequently. Foreign
                    Minister <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> set forth the militant
                    South Korean position in a letter to <persName corresp="#p_CGMW1"
                        >Clark</persName>, June 18, a copy of which is printed in the Department of
                    State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, June 29, 1953, page 906. Also in that
                    same <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, page 907, is the text of a message from
                        <persName corresp="#p_CGMW1">Clark</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName>, which was written on June 18, but is dated by the <hi
                        rend="italic">Bulletin</hi> as June 20. President <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> sent <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName> a message, drafted with the assistance of <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> and other major foreign policy advisers,
                    which is printed verbatim in <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>’s
                        <hi rend="italic">Mandate for Change</hi>, pages 185–186. Both <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CGMW1"
                        >Clark</persName> in their respective messages berated <persName
                        corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> for abrogation of his promise not to take
                    unilateral action without first consulting the United Nations Command. <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>
                    <pb facs="0082" n="1200" xml:id="pg_1200"/> stated that unless <persName
                        corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> accepted United Nations Command authority
                    to conduct the hostilities and bring them to a close, “another arrangement”
                    (unspecified) would be necessary.</p>
